rman <i>penning</i>, Middle Dutch <i>penninc</i> ‘penny’ (see   Penny  ), a topographic name (from a field name) or a nickname referring to tax dues of a penny.","South German: from the short form, <i>Panno</i>, of an ancient Germanic personal name derived from a word meaning ‘ban, order, command’.","English: from a Middle English personal name <i>Pening</i>, <i>Pining</i>, presumably representing an unrecorded Old English name, a pet form perhaps of <i>Penda</i> or of names like <i>Pendhere</i> and <i>Pendwulf</i>."]},{"name":"Pinyan","meanings":["English: variant of   Pinion  ."]}]},{"name":"Efa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of several Anglicized forms of the Gaelic name Eithne . In the case of Queen Victoria's granddaughter Princess Ena (Victoria Eugénie Julia Ena,  1887–1969 ) it had a different origin: it was a misreading by the minister who baptized her off a handwritten note of the originally intended name   Eva .  In England, the name is remembered principally as that of the fearsome  Ena Sharples  in the television soap opera Coronation Street.  See also  Ina ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eithne","meanings":["Traditional name, apparently from <i>eithne</i> ‘kernel’, which was used as a term of praise in bardic poetry. St Eithne was a daughter of King Laoghaire and one of St Patrick's first converts."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Efa Einion was born in 1329, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, her father, Einion \"Goch\" ap Einion, was 36 and her mother, Jonet ferch Ieuan, was 5. She had at least 1 daughter with Gruffudd Ap Rhys. She died in Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1329–":"1329–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1341–Male":"1341–Surnud","1343–1387":"1343–1387","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1294–Male":"1294–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1325":"1325","1387":"1387","1343":"1343","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1294":"1294","1380